(403, 108, 0, 6, 1, '2009-11-09 20:08:09', 3, 'DC', '2013', 'Ethics, Politics, and Economics', 'Dilan', 'A', 'Gomih', '20815 Sparta Lane', 'Olympia Fields', 'IL', '60461', '', '7082543264', '', '', '201499', 'New Haven', 'CT', '06520', 'G500-6419-1718', 'IL', '908862712', 'oludamilola.gomih@yale.edu', 'oludamilola.gomih@yale.edu', 1, '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Black or African American', '', 'I’m from Chicago, a city whose tedious, horn-honking, 4:00pm traffic is enough to make anyone want to learn quantum physics just to learn how to break the space-time continuum. My solution to the monotony? Good music and great conversation,  sprinkled with a few well-placed advertisements, well done and served to the greater Chicagoland Area.\n\nRadio has always been an active interest of mine, specifically the musical aspect. I have a wide variety of music interests ranging from Led Zeppelin to The Shins to Nirvana to Brandi Carlisle to the Allman Brothers Band to Metallica to Andrea Bocelli. I like to talk about music and up and coming artists—making predictions about how quickly they’re going to rock the cover of Rolling Stone or a band’s chances of becoming the next Milli Vanilli is a specialty of mine. I love watching artists creep up from the underground, take center stage, and talk about how they’ve grown. For instance,  I’ve loved Kings of Leon since Youth & Manhood (2003) when Caleb Followill still hid his voice under southern-style, garage band tones and our neighbors from across the pond received the band better than the U.S. did. Now that everybody and their cousin has “Use Somebody” as a ringtone after the success of Only By the Night domestically, I can say I knew them when…..at least metaphorically. I pay attention to when a lead guitarist experiments with a  pedal or how Autotone-loaded an album is because all the little details I think are so important to how music is supposed to make someone feel. There’s a difference between an artist who’s just trying to make it big and an artist that puts their heart and soul into their music to touch someone….and I’m looking for it, I’m talking about it, and I’m ready to broadcast it loud and clear.\n\nAlso,  I can hold a conversation. I have always been the girl to fix the silence, fix the awkwardness, to make someone laugh.  It may be a symptom of being the last born child a.k.a the Comic Relief, but I think it could work for the radio. In addition, I am a pop culture fiend, another aspect I believe I could work into whatever radio work I do.\n\nHowever, I know there is much more to learn and I’m willing to make the time and effort to be a beneficial contribution to WYBC.  I hope that you will consider my application and I look forward to hearing from you.\n\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
